The Kargil war, which began in May 1999, was announced after the infiltration of Pakistani troops and Kashmiri militants into Kargil district in Jammu and Kashmir and along the line of control. The intrusion into the area, which separated Ladakh's Indian territory from the north of the state, completely surprised the Indian army and Operation Vijay was immediately launched to drive our enemies out of the Kargil area. Pakistani soldier at center of attack It is believed that Pervez Musharraf, then head of the Pakistani army, would be the mastermind behind the attack. Musharraf carefully traced the intrusion plan, without any clarification from then Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. He was supported and assisted by General Leiutenant, Mohammed Aziz. It is said that Musharraf executed the plan while Atal Bihari Vajpayee responded to Nawaz Sharif's invitation to Lahore and that the duo signed the Lahore declaration. Conventional modes of warfare were used. MODE OF FIGHT Well equipped with weapons of war, both sides were ready to launch attacks. The 18,000-foot battle on the rocky terrain took place under extremely low temperatures, in a conventional manner, despite the fact that both sides possess nuclear weapons. India has placed five infantry divisions, five independent brigades and 44 paramilitary battalions in Kashmir and deployed 60 front-line aircraft. Former Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and Army and Air Force Officers Greet at India's Gate on Vijay Diwas INDIAN AERIAL FORCE On May 24, 1999, it was decided that the operation would be joined by the Indian Air Force (IAF). Tiger Hill, one of the highest peaks in the Drass-Kargil region, became the focus of the war. After a fierce war of more than sixty days and with the support of the international community, India has taken Tiger Hill back and repelled Pakistani forces on its territory. Schoolchildren display a national flag on an Indian Army tank to commemorate the day of the international response to the conflict. The infiltration of Pakistan into India and the military clashes have been sharply criticized by many countries and have resulted in US intervention in the crisis. According to an article in the Daily Times, one of Pakistan's leading newspapers, India has won the trust of the United States while Pakistan "loses credibility in the eyes of India and Pakistan." Q2) Can you prove that GDP data are fake? - Until January 2015, the Indian economy has experienced interesting growth since the mid-1980s. And then the magic has arrived. The Central Statistical Office (CSO) has changed the way it calculates GDP, indicating that it is necessary to do so by taking into account global practices. As a result, India was ahead of China and became the fastest growing economy. In 2013-14, our economy grew by 6.9%, up from 4.7%, as reported by civil society organizations. Even the country's chief economic advisor, Arvind Subramanian, said: "I am baffled by the new GDP growth figures. The revised figures show that GDP growth increased from 4.7% to 5.1% for 2012-13 and from 5% to 6.9% for 2013-14. This means an acceleration in GDP growth of 1.9 percentage points in 2013-2014, simply by comparing the new figures over time. "He also said that" these figures, in particular the acceleration of 2013- 2014, were at odds with other features of macroeconomics. "Almost all economic experts, whether government members or not (including Raghuram Rajan), questioned the GDP figures because they found that realities on the ground reflected a completely opposite picture.The new GDP figures appeared to be totally at odds with other economic indicators. "According to R Nagraj, an independent member of the subcommittee who reviewed the new methodology for estimating output, version adopted by the Central Stastical Organization was very different from the report finalized by the subcommittee in September 2014. Q3) Latest GDP data published after demonetization? - They are also fake. While the performances of some sectors have been better than those of previous quarters, the huge improvement in private consumption (almost doubled) seems highly doubtful given the lack of liquidity during the demonetization. It seems that the CSO was not able to map the demonetisation effect in its data. The government and the RBI have also stated (along with some of their savvy critics) that the effect of demonetization can be mapped over a longer period. In addition, the OSC downgraded the 2015-2016 third quarter estimates by 0.3 percentage points, from 7.2% earlier to 6.9%, resulting in a significant improvement in the numbers. third quarter of 2016-17. For those who do not find this surprising, the CSO has revised its estimates for the first and second quarters of 2015-2016. This downward revision of the third quarter of 2015-2016 helped to limit the effect of demonetization in figures. Q4) I can not understand anything. Why? - You will not be able to get it. You are neither a statistician nor an economist. Whenever reports and claims such as these come to light, browse the Internet a bit beyond Facebook and Twitter, and learn basic information and what the experts say. He convinced people to believe that experts know nothing. It disinforms people who know nothing but believe it. They have neither the time nor the will to discover the truth.
